{"id": "Computer_Science_95_r", "displayed_text": "<span id=\"hover_text_news\" data-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-html=\"true\" data-placement=\"bottom\" title=\"Context: [related]\n\nThe final analysis shows that the mixed-reality game improved learning by almost five times more than the screen-only alternatives, both in the mouse-controlled and physically controlled conditions. Not only that, but students enjoyed the game more in the mixed-reality conditions. They also determined that simple physical controls like shaking the tablet or pushing the earthquake button did little to improve either learning or enjoyment of the game.\"><b>Finding:</b></span> [related]\n\nThe final analysis shows that the mixed-reality game improved learning by almost five times more than the screen-only alternatives, both in the mouse-controlled and physically controlled conditions.", "label_annotations": {"how-certain-is-the-finding": {"Certain": "4"}}, "span_annotations": [{"start": 714, "end": 722, "span": "improved", "annotation": "Words indicating certainty"}], "behavioral_data": {"time_string": "Time spent: 0d 0h 1m 0s "}}
